## Playback Seam Note

- Player startup now has a dedicated playback descriptor seam: `GET /api/library/movies/{id}/playback`.
- The current backend response is still direct-play oriented and points to `/api/library/movies/{id}/stream`.
- Frontend player code should consume the playback descriptor first, then treat `/stream` as an implementation detail.
- Curated now also has two expansion paths on that seam: a **browser-side native-player handoff** path used by the current frontend (default PotPlayer protocol template `potplayer:{url}`), plus the backend session path `POST /api/library/movies/{id}/playback-session` and `/api/playback/sessions/{id}/hls/...` for HLS stream push. The older `POST /api/library/movies/{id}/native-play` backend-launch route still exists as a legacy/native-shell hook, but the player page no longer depends on it for the default local-player action.
- Playback descriptors now carry structured decision diagnostics in addition to `mode`: `sessionKind`, `reasonCode`, `reasonMessage`, `sourceContainer`, `sourceVideoCodec`, `sourceAudioCodec`.
- Playback planning is no longer extension-only. Backend resolution now probes media metadata first, then chooses between `direct-file`, `remux-hls`, and `transcode-hls`.
- HLS session startup is now remux-first when the source is already HLS-friendly (`h264` video + compatible audio), with automatic fallback to hardware/software transcode profiles if stream-copy startup fails.
- HLS session governance now includes an idle-session janitor plus diagnostics routes: `GET /api/playback/sessions/recent` and `GET /api/playback/sessions/{id}`. The manager keeps active sessions and a bounded in-memory archive of recently closed or expired sessions so those endpoints remain useful after cleanup.
- The current in-page HLS browser path loads `hls.js` on demand when native HLS is unavailable.
- `GET/PATCH /api/settings` now includes playback runtime preferences such as `nativePlayerEnabled`, `nativePlayerCommand`, `streamPushEnabled`, `ffmpegCommand`, `preferNativePlayer`, `seekForwardStepSec`, and `seekBackwardStepSec`.
- Browser protocol handoff templates are **per-machine frontend state** stored in `localStorage` under `curated-native-player-browser-template-v1`; settings UI treats this as a browser launch template rather than a backend executable path.

## 2026-04 Network Stability Update

- Actor scraping now supports backend-owned avatar caching and same-origin delivery via `GET /api/library/actors/{name}/asset/avatar`.
- Actor DTOs expose local-avatar state (`avatarLocalUrl`, `avatarRemoteUrl`, `hasLocalAvatar`), and backend handlers rewrite `avatarUrl` to the same-origin path when a cached file is ready.
- Movie preview assets still prefer local cache, and now have a backend proxy fallback when `media_assets.source_url` exists but `local_path` is missing.
- `media_assets` now persists source-side diagnostics for downloads: `source_provider`, `referer_url`, `last_http_status`, `last_error`, `last_fetched_at`.
- Settings / runtime now have a higher-level scrape scheduler field `metadataMovieStrategy` in addition to legacy `metadataMovieScrapeMode`.
- Provider health responses and task records now include richer machine-readable failure information (`errorCategory`, cooldown and rolling latency state where available).
